<P>
<A NAME="ST03.1">
<CENTER>
 <h3>
 A Logical Framework for Course Configuration in eLearning
 </h3>
<h4>A.Sterbini and M.Temperini</h4>
<h4>ABSTRACT</h4>
We outline a framework for the development of different versions (configurations)
of a same course, so to fit the different needs shown by different students.
In our framework, a didactic pool contains learning components.
A component is a container for a small part of a course,
specifying the knowledge that it requires,
the knowledge that it will eventually provide and
the related learning resources.
All those components could make up a complete and comprehensive course,
yet it is quite likely that a given student, depending on its starting
knowledge, will
need only a subset of all those components to reach the course's aims
(the target knowledge).
In order to tailor a course to the effective
student's needs,
we try to devise precise yet easily applicable ways for
modeling the course-related knowledge
and effective protocols for the use of such representations in the
configuration steps.
The representational devices used for expressing the involved knowledge
are based on propositional logic.
</CENTER>
</P>



